text:
the worst thing for me isnÂ´t the fact that it seems like nobody seems to care or understand.
the worst thing is, that the people i tell my story, are not even willing to understand. â€œyou are talking normal, so you canÂ´t be ill.â€
â€œyou are smiling, so you are not depressed. â€œ
â€œyou havenÂ´t tried to kill yourself, canÂ´t be that bad.â€
â€œjust try to think positive, you are the problem. â€œ
â€œtry to wear brighter clothes, you will feel better. â€œ
â€œyou are always so strong, you canÂ´t have a mental illness.â€ i am dealing with depression, anxiety, burnout and who knows what else, for over 10 years now. but for all this years i never talked to a specialist for mental health. i only spoke to my normal doctor and got some medicine (antidepressant).
i can recommend to everyone, that thinks â€maybe i am more, than just sad.â€œ: go to a specialised doctor and ask him or her what they think.
when i took the step and first spoke to a specialist, i was really happy to talk to someone that knows what i am going though.
donâ€™t be afraid to talk about your problems, your sadness or loneliness and your feelings! there will always be someone that can and will understand you!

text: today was also rough, as i made the decision to unfollow someone i've looked up to for 16 years. i've got nothing but love in my heart for the dude, but it's hard to see someone you care about going against what you know to be right and just. for the record: if you have a friend who is accused of sexual assault, i can absolutely understand you wanting to stand with them and question those allegations. i can understand comforting and supporting them privately. what i cannot understand is using a public platform with hudreds of thousands of followers, many of whom you know are victims of the same abuse your friend is accused of committing, many of whom have confessed their deepest, most vulnerable moments to you, to continue to promote the person under those allegations. what i absolutely refuse to condone is turning off comments specifically on certain posts to avoid any discussion on the topic from people you've very clearly hurt, people who have in the past been your strongest supporters. it all leaves a bad taste in my mouth and was all done without tact.

text:
finally, the last part of my #rebelstory with which i hoped to answer some of your questions and hopefully inspire some of you to walk the way youâ€™ve chosen, even if it often means to walk alone. â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”
today my story  continues here in western europe. the place where dreams have more chances to become reality, the place where human dignity is respected, the place where equality is advocated. however, paradoxically, also the place where all the achievements, rights are often taken for granted. the illusion that the rights people have here wont be ever taken away, the democratic process wont ever move backwards, lead many to give up, to stop carrying about their rights, to stop participating in public debates and leave all the responsibility on a small group of politicians. women sometimes chose to keep silence as they are told their status is improving and their single experiences should not be shared in public. but silence is a death penalty for our personalities and our dreams. many want us silent to prevent us from making a change. i know it well, as in 2015 not far from here, in copenhagen, i was giving a talk on freedom of speech. i couldn't express my ideas because of kalashnikov shots fired by a person moved by dogmas at the moment i was speaking on the stage. for him it was easier to take a gun and kill people than to hear a different opinion, then to accept that we have right to express our aspirations and demands. from that terrorist attack, that as other experiences had affected me for life, iâ€™ve also learned. my shaking voice became now louder and more confident. iâ€™ve learned the necessity to speak out. i said to myself we all have to be louder that their kalashnikovs. we all have to break the silence that the old rotten system expects from us. 
i tell my story simply to remind that hope can rise from despair, light from darkness, strength from weakness, courage from fearâ€¦ today, we all see how victims speak out with #metoo movement, how they manifest their strength after horrifying experiences, how they sound loud after years of silence. thatâ€™s the story... the moral is: never let anyone bully you into silence. #femen

text:
07102018 part 7
...so my ex spends time with his mom 24/7. he tells me not to go downstairs. he uses her bathroom & walks around in his underwear in front of her. they act like a real couple at home. eating side by side, going out, shopping together, walking sofia for hours, even when its late in the evening so she comes home with big mosquito bites that gets infected. he also spends time in the room with his mom with the lights out; tiptoeng out of the room. its been really disgusting. i've never seen anything like it. they dont invite me at all and when they come home they give sofia to me as if im just a caretaker. the neighbors are asking me why im always excluded. when i voice out my concerns my ex tells me its a "patriarchal house and i pay for everything so you have no say at all". ...so many things has happened in the past especially in the past 3 months. im glad that we are out of that mad house. since we left, sofia has been giggling more & shes sleeping soundly. i apologize if there is no positivity in my posts. this is about the ugly truth of a bad marriage. #domesticviolence is never pretty. when its done, all you have left are the scars & memories that will hopefully go away one day. they say time heals everything and sofia & i are waiting until it hurts no more. i know i've been through a lot but sofia has been through more because i can defend myself, speak up, & fight back. but she cant. she needs time to heal from all that carelessness & neglect. my ex tells me that if we divorce sofia will not grow up normally. i say if we dont divorce then she really wont. i know children who were raised by only their mothers who grew up well. its all about how i do it. and i know i can do it right with guidance from above. i know i can. for all you women out there dont be a victim! you are worth all the love in the world. dont be afraid to speak up & walk away. in fact, please do everything to get away! you can do it on your own. remember: god counts a woman's tears. know youre important! this society as you know it wouldnt exist without you! speak up for the truth! social media must advocate more for the truth than for pretty little things. sofia is safe!â¤

in de wake of the #metoo movement we are reading about all kinds of violations and experiences that women from all professional fields are and have suffered from... in a country thats on  the threshold of empowering women to not just speak up but also take action against the predator .. even if shez alone.. is reason enough to celebrate ... but is this enough ? will it sustain? maybe it will curb de intentions of a few creeps who may think twice before doing this or find ways to continue wid a full proof plan.

we r into betibachao... lets now work on betekosikhao... teach your young sons on how to treat a woman... that no means no..
that no woman is weak or superior.. but equal

she can be ur partner she can be ur competitor she can be ur saviour but not ur slave.

that lets get a doormat who lets u walk all over her but does not speak is good to have as home decor but not as a blessing  that u need who will challenge u to b a better version of yourself.. lets teach our lil boys that hitting a woman is not ok... pushing her around is not... over powering her is not.

that when they grow up... with power comes responsibility... and de biggest challenge is knowing how to use it... lets focus on educating boys.

the beautiful thing about learning is no one can ever take it away from you.

text:
navigating relationships in the time of â€˜performance anxietyâ€™.
.
framing debates for ourselves in a time when we are still processing the what, why, and how of the absurd narratives, personalities, and the traits we missed, is not an easy task. the conversations are affecting a lot more than we notice, and nobody is able to navigate them. unlearning where we have come from and remapping relationships is a step-by-step process, nuanced in individual situations, and depending on patience to support it.
.
sharing links to some articles/books/people, i have come across in the past few months, some are more applicable to my life directly than not, but it opens up the nuances of the debate. if you have any other forms of writing, films, debates and more, that have allowed you to explore this uncharted territory with a little help, let me know.
.

text:
a little girl awoke 
at midnight,
with clenched fists,
sweaty forehead, 
and a heavy heart.

she looked around
but found nothing,
just the monster
created by her thoughts.

sadly,
it wasn't just a delusion.
she could feel
a hand 
crawling
from her waist 
under her little skirt.

it was her uncle
who asked her 
for a kiss
and to keep it a secret, 
he would give her
her favourite chocolates.

before this day
she did know
how to deal with 
the monster that hid
under her bed
but
she didn't know
how to deal 
with the monster
on her bed.

text:
wow!! such an eye-opener!!
.
makes such a huge difference when we hear or talk, or reference in the active voice.
.
interesting use of the word 'political', because it suddenly makes so much sense in how it helps in underplaying or minimizing the impact of the problem or wrong-doing.
.
high time we start talking or hearing or labelling the perpetrator, rather than the victim. high time we hear it like it actually is.
.
most interestingly, it would be our boys and young men who will quickly be taught who they should not be, or what they should not do. and, how they can become a part of the problem if they behave or do certain wrong things.
.
also, they would eventually learn how girls and women are to be protected and respected. and, not harassed or violated in any way.
.
.
.

text:
(part 2)

further, mr ganapathy notes that the accusations are made against the â€œhigh and mightyâ€. it may be that accusations against the famous are the ones that get primetime media coverage. the hindu reported on october 16, 2018 that scores of women raised the issue of being molested during the open street festival held on october 13, 2018 in mysore. in light of their statements on social media platforms, the karnataka state womenâ€™s commission has takenÂ suo motoÂ cognizance of the matter and has begun investigations. there was no one high or mighty involved in this case. mr ganapathy seems to suggest that men cannot be blamed for their instinctive behaviour since â€œafter food, animals seek sexâ€. this is particularly ironic since the incident occurred during a food festival.

revealing that his ignorance extends from biology to the law, mr ganapathy also points to a mythological legal provision that requires women to register protest at the time of a sexual assault, in the absence of which she is deemed to have given consent. given that mr ganapathy refers to hamletâ€™s queen gertrude and her discomfort in being reminded of her haste to remarry after the death of her husband, one wonders whether mr ganapathy has some discomfort of his own with regard to the issue of sexual abuse that he is so eager to decry a movement of survivors of abuse trying to air their grievances. i would urge the editor-in-chief to not use the star of mysore as a platform to air his witlessness. me thinks mr ganapathy protests the protests too much!

the original poem was from the book ' i am a woman, and i am an indian.'
_____

me too is a viral hashtag that was/is spread against assault and harassment on women. the scale with which women from around the globe participated, and now in india clearly suggested how many have faced the blunt terror of this masculine world. if this is the state of women from creamy layer and of the upper class that knows social media and hashtag, then imagine the situation of women from deprived and suburban background.

read the poem below
_______

misogyny in society â€“
in form of discrimination,

cw: se*ual ab*se
i am about to completely let my guard down for... whoever may see this. this isnâ€™t for views. this isnâ€™t so i can be â€œtrendyâ€ or â€œcoolâ€. my hair is wild, iâ€™m in my underwear, and i just finished crying. today i came to the realization that i have serious ptsd. some bad memories from when i was a child have come up. and i spent tonight crying, shaking, rocking back and forth trying to just process it all. as an adult we are taught to just let the past go. to pretend that what happened cannot and doesnâ€™t have to impact you later on. thatâ€™s bullshit. our pasts heavily dictate who we are obviously so why wouldnâ€™t we worry about it? reflect and grow. thatâ€™s what iâ€™m trying. i came to the realization though that i had a (not so close) family member sexually abuse me when i was younger. i just know it happened. idk if anyone will believe me because itâ€™s been so many years. and people may fucking... idk assume that because i couldnâ€™t remember it until now that itâ€™s fake. this isnâ€™t fake. this feeling i had cannot be faked. my entire childhood has been stripped down and taken away from me. i have no childhood anymore. i never talk about my feelings really. and i am taking this time to show you this side of me because i want anyone who is dealing with this kind of shit to know you are not alone. you truly arenâ€™t. everyoneâ€™s experiences with trauma may be different. but that doesnâ€™t mean you have to cope alone. donâ€™t do that to yourself, seriously. donâ€™t take on this trauma alone. itâ€™s okay to develop a support group to fall on when youâ€™re struggling. and if you donâ€™t have one. well fuck, now you do. iâ€™m your dad now. message me. call me. whatever you need to do. iâ€™ll be there. and if you donâ€™t have my contact information dm me and you will. when i say i love each and every one of my children (you) i mean it. youâ€™re loved. and while whatever youâ€™re going through may be hard. if you stay youâ€™ll get through it. bb. you gotta keep that chin up and keep moving forward anyway you can. stay safe. stay hydrated. love you. .
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
women long oppressed globally, stood up for their rights and unfortunately got fooled by the term of women empowerment. 
searching for equality and respect has landed women in shame, exploitation, harassment and made them an object used for selling almost any and every 'thing' & 'service' 
1. you  don't have to be dressing yourself in a manner to show case yourself. women are not public property. respect your body. cover it! 
2. various addictions don't make you cool or hip. they only help men take advantage of you. needless to say what these addictions do to your health

3. working should be your choice not necessity to prove that you are as talented as a male. it should be to make you happy not slog away silently so that you prove you are educated. 
4. don't look down upon women who choose to be homemakers. not many men can do half as good to manage home and they don't try to prove they are good at everything. why do women have to prove anything? 
5. staying out late at nights doesn't make you strong or equal a male. it only gives opportunity to weak uneducated males to commit crimes. stay safe... women empowerment does not mean what the above creative says.. empowerment means to be free to choose and not having to prove your worth while being safe and not be objectified

#women #empowerment #womenempowerement #safety #respect #goodvibes #homemaker #proud #wife #daughter #sister #educated #power #loyal #notanobject #strong #intelligent #smart #metoo #movement

text:
on wednesday, 17th october 2018, the womenâ€™s development cell at ahmedabad university will host a talk on â€˜#metoo #wdc' by dr ranjana harish (former professor and head, department of english, school of languages and director, reaney canadian study centre, gujarat university). addressing issues around gender inequalities and womenâ€™s safety, the talk will focus on the need to sensitise the privileged gender/s about the problems of the marginalised. as founder convener of womenâ€™s development cell in gujarat university, dr ranjana harish is uniquely qualified to lead the interactive session which seeks to gain from the valuable inputs of the participants and work towards furthering the sensibility of gender equality.

students, faculty members, and friends, save the date.

join us at gict building (lecture theatre 105; 2:15â€“3:15 pm) to understand how we can work together and contribute to the success of this mammoth task.

text:
an ode to #metoo and to every woman suffering, fighting, surviving, emerging and living:
look outside your castle.
from the dull stairs and washed walls
you'll see a canopy of trees
and a garden of roses.
those roses have thorns
and those trees are a haven to snakes.
but you're a warrior.
you will build your armour
and you will fight the venom with every antidote
that you will always find within you.
let not the snakes make you fret
or fear your ambitions.
ultimately you possess what they don't:
substance apart from venoms.
.
.
.
.

text:
(part 1/3)
disclaimer- some parts of the incident might be disturbing. 
whenever i am asked to describe one of  my least favourite memories as a child, my mind instantly jumps onto this one incident. itâ€™s hard to put incidents like these into words but one must do it because it can happen with anyone, irrespective of the gender and it needs to be talked about more because #timesup. i was about 5 and he must have been in his 20s. he was our relativesâ€™ driver. the distance from my house to my extended familyâ€™s house was roughly a 5 minute walk. he used to call me â€˜pariâ€™ and tell
me that i was his favourite kid. i used to call him my favourite uncle as well. our entire family had immense trust in him. i had a habit of staying up late at their house after playing and my mom used to pick me up. this one night, she couldnâ€™t. so he was supposed to walk me home. i was extremely sleepy so i went with it. i just wanted to get home and get some sleep. what i thought was a mere 5 minute walk, turned out be the most painful 5 minutes of my life. he started by playing with my fingers and licking them, i thought he was being funny but he slowly went his way up and forcefully tried kissing me, multiple times. i was horrified. i didnâ€™t know what exactly was happening but i knew it was wrong. he then touched me in highly inappropriate ways. i knew it didnâ€™t feel right. i froze and started crying, running towards my house. the gate was tall so i couldnâ€™t reach it. i just kept on sobbing. he came running towards me and said multiple sorries,wiped my face, gave me a chocolate and hushed me. that was the first night as a child i remember i couldnâ€™t sleep. i became absolutely scared of him and he gave me nightmares for months. my mom and everyone questioned my behaviour and sudden dislike towards him but i couldnâ€™t put it in words. i used to run and hide in closet everytime i saw him.this went on for a while until he finally quit his job. i was 7 by now and was just relieved at the fact that i donâ€™t have to face him but inside i was still terrified.
â€”

text:
(part 2/3)
it was only after i grew up and learned about sexual abuse through an article that i realized i had been a victim as well. after he left, there were couple of times i saw him but i stopped running away. i starred at him with utter disgust and completely ignored him and he tried approaching me several times but failed. i slowly started realizing the difference between right and wrong. it took me years to tell this to my mom and she was horrified and extremely sorry but she was happy that i was well and alive. i have never told this to anyone else besides her and a couple of close friends and family. i know i am definitely not the only one in this and i know that it wasnâ€™t my fault. â€¢
that is just one of the multiple incidents that i can recall. another one that happened to me was on facebook when i added this guy who went to our rival school. it began with the usual hiâ€™s and helloâ€™s until one time he ended up sending me an unsolicited picture of his genitalia. i was too naive and kept on wondering how could someone send their naked pictures to someone theyâ€™ve just met. to my horror, my mom found about it and went ballistic. i was petrified and utterly confused. i immediately blocked him without saying a word. i thought he was just being a creep. after that, two of the guys i ended up liking turned out to be the biggest jerks. one of them called me names because things went sour with our so called friendship and the other one falsely accused me of engaging in inappropriate acts just for his â€œfunâ€ and because it made him laugh. there have been a lot of times where iâ€™ve been called names right in front of my face and the countless number of inappropriate comments lying in my â€œotherâ€ facebook messages folder and direct messages,full of desperate men. â€¢

text:
(part 3/3)
iâ€™ve talked to my peers about sexual harassment and their carefree attitude appalls me. the fact that most of the women have been victimized at some point or the other in their lives, and yet they choose to neglect it, infuriates me. weâ€™ve been so conditioned to behave in a certain way just because weâ€™re girls, that weâ€™ve given a way to normalize sexual misconduct because â€œlog kya kahengeâ€ and worse if itâ€™s on social media because thatâ€™s not â€œreal harassmentâ€. our conditioned mindset is the reason why we as victims have been blaming ourselves and this is exactly why need a movement like #metoo. it isnâ€™t just a plethora of women sharing their stories. itâ€™s about coming together and standing up against the overdue abuse that weâ€™re forced to endure, even though my heart breaks thinking about how restricted weâ€™ve been that we needed a movement to share our stories. in the recent wake of #metoo, i have read about millions of comments asking the victims about what took them so long to speak up. and that nobody cares, because they could be making this up falsely for purely attention seeking reasons. first of all, each person processes pain differently. sexual abuse is not just physical or limited to the cyberspace. itâ€™s about the mental torture and struggle that the victim goes through. there is a multi-layered healing process that can take as long as a lifetime to overcome the pain and torture. itâ€™s about dealing with the shame, the shock and the courage to speak out. itâ€™s not something you do for attention. secondly, people do tend to over react and misuse the law without even realizing it. if someone is speaking about how they felt uncomfortable in a relationship, youâ€™ve no right to deny or call them out just because it doesnâ€™t â€œmeet the guidelines of #metooâ€. the movement is not an institution, its not gender specific, itâ€™s about standing up to the society and telling them that weâ€™re done with their shit and brave enough to call them out on it. so i request the people reading this  to be more kind because thatâ€™s the least you can do, without judging the victims. you donâ€™t know it until you go through it. â€”

text:
i've got excuses a plenty. *my mom is in town!!! *tired from work *ladyness cramps *kids need help getting tasks done *it's late
*i want donuts *did i mention my mom is here?!?!?!? i could let things get in the way. but folks, life happens!! we can use every excuse in the book..but, when you start wanting it for yourself bad enough... when you keep the promises you make to yourself... when you know that taking care of yourself makes it easier to take care of others... that's when you visit with your mom while you chisel your shoulders :) you don't have to choose. you can have & do all the things. and eat the donuts too ;) #youareenough #selflove #bodylove #selfcare #juststart #loveyourself #metoo #lovemymom #creatingabettermeforme #andforthem #onwardandupward

text:
really, why worry?
personal vengeances are one thing. and it is a very cheap tactic to get back at someone by defaming and those who are found to be guilty of defaming another person must be punished. but the truth is, such things won't prevail and truth always wins.
more importance needs to be given to the actual movement rather than the collateral damages that can be fixed. no one is charging anybody here. women are just speaking up for once.

text:
i stitched this while contemplating the word "no". i used to have a t-shirt, bright red and in white block letters was the word "no". that shirt got me a lot of male attention. one man after another would ask "no what?" some of them would ask as we interacted about something else,  some would approach me out of nowhere to ask what my shirt meant. as i continued to stitch, it occurred to me when these men asked the question, their tones varied. some asked playfully, some confused, but most of the time their tone wasn't inquisitive. the majority didn't ask me a question so much as demand an answer - "no what?" no permission? no access? no thank you? just no? 
the very existence of "no" was foreign to them, offensive even. "no" just wasn't on their radar, so the minute they detected it- beep beep beep here they came running, demanding to know what exactly it was they were being denied. 
i find this very telling. even more telling is the fact that i never had to explain to a  woman what my shirt meant. not one ever asked. 
#handembroidery #embroidery #threadtherapy #threadhead #hoophoe #metoo #nomeansno #malefragility #maletears #stitchtober day 15

text:
jennifer part 2: itâ€™s an uncomfortable topic, and i see so many people who donâ€™t understand what it feels like to be dehumanized on that level, outwardly judging people and what theyâ€™ve gone through. sexual assault is a crime against humanity, and i think itâ€™s devastatingly sad to see our countryâ€™s leader openly trying to invalidate multiple, credible womenâ€™s stories to serve his political agenda. whatever happened to justice, and protecting the innocent? itâ€™s time for more of us to speak up about this, because it isnâ€™t just a problem for victims, but itâ€™s everyoneâ€™s problem. what if it was you, or someone you loved?

itâ€™s heartbreakingly sad for me to say that iâ€™ve been a victim of sexual assault on multiple occasions. i need to be open with all of you about exactly what those experiences, and the aftermath felt like.

helpless. gripped with fear. deeply shamed. worthless. voiceless. sick. isolated from others. damaged, like a lesser human being. inferior, like nothing i could ever do would make me whole again, or even equal to others. humiliated. bound to silence. dishonored. i felt like no one would ever understand. i have suffered in silence for a long time. i have had suicidal thoughts. i have struggled for years trying to prove to others i had worth, trying to be good enough because of this underlying fear that who i am isnâ€™t enough. i have experienced the deepest level of shame and depression. i have blamed myself. i thought maybe this evil, dehumanizing behavior of another is somehow my fault. i have had so much to overcome. these experiences have attacked the core of who i am.

text:
jennifer part 3: this is really just a short snapshot of the experiences, and what i went through after that. by sharing my story, i want others to know just how evil and damaging sexual assault is. it shouldnâ€™t be a common experience. it shouldnâ€™t be joked about or laughed at. what if it was you? i want people to fight to protect and honor those who werenâ€™t protected. i want people to speak up. i want to be fought for, and i want to fight for others. 
this photo is a part of a collaboration to bring awareness to this issue, .... this photo is a part of a collaboration to bring awareness to this issue. if you or someone you know wants to be a part of this body of work (replicating the image of being bound with duct tape/wearing a red tie), please reach out to me, my friend @carolinenicolehaag or @kevinirelan 
every voice matters.

text: a rough draft of something i want to make. it's from ecclesiastes 3:7, and i feel like it's something sexual abuse survivors need to hear. do not feel shamed for not telling when it happened, whether it was years ago or days ago. there are reasons we don't tell. it's your experience and your story to share when you are ready. i pray that when you do speak, you would be surrounded by those who will hear you, come alongside you, believe you, and help you decide what steps you are ready to take towards healing. #metoo #churchtoo #handlettered #handlettering #leftylettering #leftyletterer #leftycalligraphers #ecclesiastes #moderncalligraphy

text:
jennifer part 1: the person i want to be is authentic, honest, and courageous. while those are some of my deepest values, the truth is that sometimes itâ€™s hard to speak up, and bring that level of transparency to a social media platform, especially when itâ€™s something so deeply personal, and has been a source of emotional pain for me for a long time.

when the #metoo movement started, i wanted to post something because iâ€™m a part of that group, but i didnâ€™t want the importance of my story to be diminished in any way, because of just how common it was becoming to see these posts from people in my facebook friend groups. the sad part of it is exactly that--that itâ€™s becoming such a common experience, which means itâ€™s becoming such a big big problem. turning a blind eye to injustice is wrong. 
there are many people i talk to who are flippant about those experiences and think the victim is just trying to get attention, or ruin another personâ€™s life, or that their experience is somehow invalid. this is a pretty ignorant perspective to take, especially when it takes so much courage to speak up in the first place.

text:
red trauma,  mix media on canvas , 2013
.
.
abuse is any childâ€™s worst nightmare; physical abuse can wound human soul terribly when it comes with sexual assault. my work is about such experiences which i have lived through every day once when it was happening and now when it has happened. i paint self-portraits as my catharsis, i have tried words earlier but this has served me more than any medium. itâ€™s a cage of my own self which never let me out. itâ€™s not only me; itâ€™s every other person in different prison of inner self hiding othersâ€™ mistakes. i have lived through it and will be breathing through it. all that dirt poured on my soul was not mine, how it could be; i was just a child, i was â€˜sheâ€™. my work is a narration of my emotional struggle being a survivor of sexual abuse mainly. it is a statement about psychological and emotional impact of abuse on children as well as adults. our social taboos does not allow women as well as men to raise a voice about their sufferings which makes it more suffocating. we don't have a way out of this because we don't have any one to listen or understand. .
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
blue trauma, mix media on canvas,  2013
.
.
abuse is any childâ€™s worst nightmare; physical abuse can wound human soul terribly when it comes with sexual assault. my work is about such experiences which i have lived through every day once when it was happening and now when it has happened. i paint self-portraits as my catharsis, i have tried words earlier but this has served me more than any medium. itâ€™s a cage of my own self which never let me out. itâ€™s not only me; itâ€™s every other person in different prison of inner self hiding othersâ€™ mistakes. i have lived through it and will be breathing through it. all that dirt poured on my soul was not mine, how it could be; i was just a child, i was â€˜sheâ€™. my work is a narration of my emotional struggle being a survivor of sexual abuse mainly. it is a statement about psychological and emotional impact of abuse on children as well as adults. our social taboos does not allow women as well as men to raise a voice about their sufferings which makes it more suffocating. we don't have a way out of this because we don't have any one to listen or understand. .
.

text:
i donâ€™t recognize the girl on left...
she was sick, she was sad, she was broken, she was lost... mostly tho, she was drinking...
***trigger warning âš ï¸ ****
a lot has changed in the last 2.5 years, &not my weight (believe it or not, i weigh the same in both photos).
i decided i needed to heal, and started to make changes, i got off anti depressant/anxiety meds, which i had been on for 6 years(i felt really ready and talked to my doctors, itâ€™s not recommended for everyone). i decided that i needed to really dig down deep to start healing, and altho those meds were helpful, they didnâ€™t help heal me. 
ive dealt with darkness my whole life... having a fatal disease, and being told by doctors at a very young age i didnâ€™t have much of chance of seeing my 18th birthday was always hard, i spent a lot of time in hospital, i missed a lot of school and often kids were cruel, they didnâ€™t want to be friends with a kid who was sick. 
but i suffered a major trauma at 22, i was a virgin and was drugged and raped.
shortly after sank down into a very very dark place. i went through trauma therapy, and counselling, which was helpful. but it wasnâ€™t until about 2 years ago that i started talking about it with other women who had also been through sexual trauma that i actually started to heal.
because nothing sends you down into darkness faster than feeling utterly alone in something youâ€™ve experienced...and nothing more uplifting and freeing then realizing youâ€™re not alone. 
i realized that my heavy drinking needed to stop... it was killing me, body and soul. 
so i cut back, a lot. 
it wasnâ€™t until i got together with my loving, supportive and sober partner @mccaffreym2 that i really was able to kick the habit. itâ€™s really incredible what having a good support system will do for the healing process. 
all that being said, not everyone has that special person in their lives...and iâ€™d like to extend a hand, to anyone struggling, who wants to change or wants to heal. iâ€™m here for you. itâ€™s not easy, to be honest itâ€™s scary as hell. but nothing is more worth it. itâ€™s incredible what happens, the light that start to stream in when you decide to step out of the darkness.

text:
time for some rather long oversharing, my hands are sweating as i type this. it's been a year since the #metoo movement went viral in the wake of the weinstein case, over ten years after first being launched by activist tarana burke. one year later things haven't gotten much better, particularly given the confirmation of brett kavanaugh. i don't quite have the words for how incredibly distressing this all has been. i've only recently made the decision to take the first steps of sharing my stories. recently, @amandapalmer and jasmine power released a video for their song 'mr. weinstein will see you now' (which i greatly encourage you to watch and listen to). it greatly inspired me to start creating some very vaunerable art surrounding my experiences and existing in my body as a survivor. i wanted to use motifs prevalent in the video because watching it for the first time was such an intensely cathartic and empowering experience and i don't think i've ever connected to another piece of art like that. 
if you've read this far, thank you. 
more to come, as i am planning a new series on the subject.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
creating controversial content is never easy.  it is not meant to be. controversial conversations involve confronting issues, sometimes these issues are unsavory and culturally pertinent. 
over the last 48 hours several women have expressed that our micro-short while a tribute to broken home lands and religious turmoil, reminds them of the violence women experience in these countries and how we hide under the blanket of â€œcultural normalcyâ€ when we fail to get involved or help individuals experiencing domestic violence or sexual harrasment
.
as the #metooindia movement finally surfaces, i as an american- indian woman, ask of my internet friends, that you stop allowing violence and atrocities towards any gender because you feel the culture deems it appropriate or normal.  do not let your brothers, sisters, mothers, fathers, children and friends suffer because an antiquated society has taught you too
.
be brave. unlearn and speak up
@suswana_sohinee .

.
.
.
.

text:
ajeeb baat hay, bachpan se he shaadi k liye tyaar karna shuru kar daitay hain, khana banana, safai rakhna, uthnay aur baithnay ka saleeka, apne shohar ka khyaal rakhna, lekin kabhi koi jinsi taluqaat k baray mein toh kuch nahin batata. kuch batana bhi nahin, aur khud se seekhna bhi nahin. porn, ghalat baat! mills & boon novels, ghalat baat! practice, matlab maut.
when in school, a teacher overheard us talking about sex, as a consequence we were sent to the headmistressâ€™s office, there, we were forced to write an apology on a pink paper which went into our files and was later shown to our parents. an apology? for having a healthy discussion about sex? amongst friends? aaj tak kuch samajh nahin ayi. i hated my school, its administration, their rules were arbitrary and humiliation was used as a form of punishment. we were humiliated for crossing the ground to meet the boys on the other side, for talking to them, sitting with them, for having any sort of contact with them and yet a course called ethics (wuttt) was introduced to the girls section to prepare us for them, for marriage. this course taught us many things: how to sit, how to eat, how to wear a dupatta, how to bake, how to fold napkins, how to make a bed, all of which i unlearnt. wife 101 wouldâ€™ve been a more appropriate name for the course, how to be the perfect wife without ever having sex. nobody educated us about sex, let alone non consensual sex. nobody talked about rape or molestation or any kind of sexual harassment. 
our mothers used to say, â€˜koi bhi haath lagaye, chahe mard ho ya aurat, toh humein ah kar batana,â€™ but since our school made us feel so ashamed of having any contact with the opposite sex, we figured, to avoid humiliation, it would be best if we remained quiet about the man who squeezed our breasts, and the man who groped our butts, and the man who grabbed our vaginas. #metoo yaar. 
acha, khair, baat yeh nahin thi, baat yeh thi keh schools ko sex education shuru kar daini chaiye. itni koi sharam ki baat nahin. ethics type courses per ziada sharmindagi honi chaiye. aur agar schools yeh initiative nahin laitay, toh maa baap ko laina chaiye.

.

text:
as many of you all know or may not know i am a survivor of #sexualabuse. however, this  post is not about my story.  this is about @katiemeyler and her non profit organization @morethanme. this very topic is what i am dedicating my life to. the culture of liberian men sleeping or abusing young children is prevalent (almost normal) that many of us are told to keep quiet, move on, forgive and forget. at this time i refuse to keep quiet. iâ€™ll move on with my voice loud. iâ€™ll forgive but never forget. 
more than me your vision of â€œevery girl empoweredâ€ is flawed. your mission of protecting children is not exemplified through your actions and the true insensitivity to what has happened to these girls before and after coming in contact with you. you had a relationship with a man who abused/raped and infected girls who you were set to protect.  you obtained millions and millions of dollars at the expense of the innocence of girls. you persuaded millions of people to donate at the cost of many girls getting aids. you manipulated girls into thinking you could save them from the streets but gave them false hope. your greed allowed you to keep these girls in a cycle of sexual exploitation. you promised to make your dream come true at the detriment of generations. you temporarily stepped down but the lives of these girls will be changed forever 
but what about the government? what about the people of the country. children are the hope for the future but why are they not protected ? why is sexual abuse swept under the rug? why in the african community is seeking help a sign of weakness. why are the victims/ survivors frowned upon but never the abuser. why is the more than me foundation still running under the same board of directors. what is the plan? the co-founder and itâ€™s board must go before the law. 
i pray these survivors find the strength to continue to be bold. to be free and heal their wounds. iâ€™m asking for everyone to join me in prayer to keep the victims and their families lifted as this is a trying time in their lives. i pray that the government will prevail and justice will be served. lord i ask that these survivors find peace within you. â¤ï¸

respect starts young. from an early age, young people receive limiting and harmful messages about how girls and boys should behave and be treated. one in four girls is the victim of sexual violence by age 18, and 7 in 10 girls are sexually harassed in high school.

girls alone cannot fix this - nor should they have to. itâ€™s going to take each and every one of us. the problem is vast but change is achievable.

text: 1 in 4 women will suffer at least one miscarriage, i  personally know over 25 women who have, including myself.  yet it is taboo to talk about.  the hardest part is moving on from something that has no understanding or solid  object of blame. how one week your little peanut can have a steady and strong heart beat and the next week your womb is empty.  how you can go to an appointment on a friday and sunday night deliver a still born.  there is no name for women/men who loose a child because the devastation of such a lost can not be captioned.  the worst part is not knowing why or how it keeps happening. i  coped by doing research  on hormones in the long term affects of birth control  and other things that make women vulnerable to miscarriages. so today we take time to  bring awareness and continue to  advocate, as we remember those sweet angels  iâ€™m advocating for the mothers who has lost  and living with the ongoing sense of pain .for  fathers that feels that lost double because essentially looses a baby and a part of his wife or partner. may you be blessed  with the numbing power of laughter and love of your other children.  #doula #comadres  #metoo #jmt.5 #8/19/12

text:
#metoo
.
.
i recently experienced the all too common ass slap from someone who i thought i was a trusted yoga instructor (someone who happens to be a 60 year-old white male). this was the second time it happened. the first time i brushed it off as something accidental - maybe it was a playful slap aiming for the leg, but happened to get the wrong spot. this time it was clear that it was not. 
i happened to be going to this class with onyxâ€™s dad, who witnessed it. he was totally horrified and distraught. ready to totally write off the yoga scene, saying that itâ€™s full of predatory men who take advantage of women in tight yoga clothes. while this is unfortunately true in some cases, i let him know that sexual assault and harassment is a societal problem. it exists across the board, and swept under the rug again, and again - #kavanaugh doesnâ€™t even need mentioning here, but it so blatantly displays all that is wrong in this country, and this happened to occur right before that trial. i also let him know that this was not the first time this happened to me in my lifetime, nor the worst scenario, and sadly it likely wonâ€™t be the last. 
this event sparked a great conversation between he and i, around this topic, and how we want to raise our daughter in this world - so i see the light in the experience. there were moments after it happened that i found myself unsettled by the yoga scene. i was letting someone take away the healing of this practice. but i decided to say nope. iâ€™m not going to let someone have that power over me. someone who clearly needs more healing than. so iâ€™m focusing on compassion, and modeling the change i wish to see to all the young lives i impact as a mother and teacher. my voice may be one, but i have the power to impact many. the narrative is shifting, and change is coming.
.
.
.
#endpatriarchy #mother #teacher #lover #femininerising #divinefeminine #feminist #yoga #yogacommunity #malasana #spirituality #healing #forgiveness #selflove #motherhoodrising

.

text:
deep. juicy. vibrant. electric. when women come together, there is a certain magic that is both palpable and inexplicable.

when we step foot on the path of healing and transformation, it becomes essential to surround ourselves with a supportive community of people who can hold space for us to go through our process. given the context of our current #metoo culture, it has never felt so crucial to surround ourselves with soulful sisters as we embark on a journey to reclaim our sexual sovereignty.

it's not always easy to cultivate this kind of relationship with other women in the context of our regular lives. we are conditioned to believe that women are critical, competitive, catty, and even vicious. and after generations of socialized behavior, we often show up that way. 
does this sound familiar to you? it doesn't have to be this way. 
knowing how many women struggle in their relationships with women, i wove into the fabric of my programs the kind of compassion, connection, and intimacy that serves as a foundation for healing and reinventing what's possible inside of sisterhood.

one of the most compelling things you will get from your participation in my upcoming 12-week program, holy sexy you, is the opportunity to be held in the safety of a pod of powerful women who are each on a parallel journey to find their way home to themselves.

i invite you to consider what it might mean for you at this point in your journey to spend some time in the structured company of women doing deep, transformational work. what might that bring to your life at this time?

learn more: link in bio

#sisterhood #transformation #sexuality #holysexyyou #women #spirituality #tantra #metamorphosis #spiritualpath

text:
dear glory baby,

you behold heavenâ€™s light, gloryâ€™s morning never fading. and though your loss brings gloomâ€™s shadow, we rejoice in knowing you'll never know true darkness, you'll never know the night.
and i will never feel your warmth, your little form in elbowâ€™s crook. yet my arms lift up hallelujahs to your maker, who has hemmed you into his wings eternal. stitch by glorious stitch. 
our souls rub sore, realizing you are absent from your sister-twin, your kindred half. yet you are honored in her every moment. every breath is a memoir. every laugh a requiem. 
and though you never made your mark, no footprints, nor heartbeatâ€” you are forever impressed upon ours. and ours, my little love, will always beat in hopeful expectation until the moment our eyes meet. 
you are always loved, you are never forgotten.

love, 
your mommy forever

it has been decided! i will call this piece "resiliance". â˜‰

i decided on this name for a few reasons... 1. i have struggled this year having being let go and non stop job hunting weighing on my self confidence and self worth.
2. there has been a lot of negative news in the world. whether it be ongoing war in the throughout the world, sexual assault/harassment and the #metoo movement, and the ongoing shootings and terrorism that seems to be on constant rerun in the news to name a few. and yet throughout all of this i'm constantly in awe of the resilience that is shown by survivors.
3. with its textured yellow bursting through and rising up against the heavy black makes my heart sing and reminds me of the light stamping out the dark, and the good overcoming the bad. â˜‰

a great reminder for all of us. no matter how big or how small our struggles are with hard work and resilience we can make a difference and we can rise up.

text: "even as we must treat accusers with seriousness and dignity, we must hear out the accused fairly and respectfully, and recognize the potential lifetime consequences that such an allegation can bring," writes emily yoffe in an atlantic article about the fallout from the brett kavanaugh hearings. "if believing the woman is the beginning and the end of a search for the truth, then we have left the realm of justice for religion." we should expect the formal arbiters of justiceâ€”police, prosecutors, judges, juries, etc.â€”to take an even-handed approach to such cases. and we should want the informal arbiters of justiceâ€”media, activists, the broader publicâ€”to exercise some degree of caution. an activist culture at war with the principles of due process and the broader presumption of innocence is a bigger threat to black convenience-store kids as it is to rich and powerful men. justice for victims must not come at the expense of fairness for the accused."- robby soave #feminism #metoo #fourthwavefeminism

text:
#newepisodeğŸ§â€¢
â€¢
our latest episode is featuring lawyer, writer, & advocate nicki hamilton, @toomanynix.

nicki shared with us her story, and we were left in awe of her bravery & strength.

nicki was living what she describes as a perfect life up until the age of 14. this was the age when new circumstances meant that nicki no longer had to spend as much time at home as usual. in typical teenage behavior, this is when she began explore life outside of her normal routine. she met new friends, went new places, and found new parts of herself. as most do when presented with new opportunities. unfortunately for nicki, her new found freedom was short lived. she quickly caught the eye of her small townâ€™s most notorious young trouble maker who decided to pursue her relentlessly. in fact, he went on to sexually assault her twice, stalk her at home and at school, send people to track her whereabouts, and slowly control every aspect of nickiâ€™s young life. 
in this interview, nicki describes exactly how, in just a few short weeks, her life changed forever. she shifted into a fearful teenager who was being stalked by her abuser. and because she was afraid of the possibility of accusations and repercussions from her family and the people of her town she internalized the experience and decided that what was happening was her own fault, rape was sex, and that she needed to create an unattractive version of herself in order to survive. so, in turn, she withdrew, became mean, and started to dress in baggy clothes.

later in life, she found therapy and landed her feet on a path towards healing. in this episode, nicki helps us understand the signs of someone who may be silently crying out for help and she provides valuable tips on what to and not to say to a victim. â€¢
â€¢
click our linktree link in the bio to listen to this empowering story or find us on your favorite podcast app.â€¢

our latest episode is featuring lawyer, writer, & advocate nicki hamilton, @toomanynix.

nicki shared with us her story, and we were left in awe of her bravery & strength.

nicki was living what she describes as a perfect life up until the age of 14. this was the age when new circumstances meant that nicki no longer had to spend as much time at home as usual. in typical teenage behavior, this is when she began explore life outside of her normal routine. she met new friends, went new places, and found new parts of herself. as most do when presented with new opportunities. unfortunately for nicki, her new found freedom was short lived. she quickly caught the eye of her small townâ€™s most notorious young trouble maker who decided to pursue her relentlessly. in fact, he went on to sexually assault her twice, stalk her at home and at school, send people to track her whereabouts, and slowly control every aspect of nickiâ€™s young life. 
in this interview, nicki describes exactly how, in just a few short weeks, her life changed forever. she shifted into a fearful teenager who was being stalked by her abuser. and because she was afraid of the possibility of accusations and repercussions from her family and the people of her town she internalized the experience and decided that what was happening was her own fault, rape was sex, and that she needed to create an unattractive version of herself in order to survive. so, in turn, she withdrew, became mean, and started to dress in baggy clothes.

later in life, she found therapy and landed her feet on a path towards healing. in this episode, nicki helps us understand the signs of someone who may be silently crying out for help and she provides valuable tips on what to and not to say to a victim. â€¢

text:
mgtow 101: the transpocalypse trojan horse

i can't believe i'm just seeing the big picture of this rights for all, equality bullshit. from a spiritual standpoint lgbt agenda is an enemy, just as much as feminists are the enemy. as they say the enemy of your enemy is an ally. women are going to be phased back into the kitchens by their own doing.

this is about to explode in stupid liberal feminist faces so hard. they don't even see what they are doing to themselves and their own daughters. . imagine the 2023 women ncaa basketball championship game with all trannies. not one woman will be given a scholarship.

there will come a time when each female sport will be dominated by men in wigs. every scholarship will be taken, their spaces will be taken. the olympics will be all men, some with wigs and some without.

give it some time, there will be one court case that allows transgenders to get female scholarships. from that moment on, women will be phased out of the entire ncaa woman's sports roster, in colleges all over.

how can a team compete with just giving scholarships to women, they will have to change up or face lawsuits. then the same will happen with ufc, women's boxing, women's soccer, wnba (already has trannies in it) and every other female sport.

even academic female reserved scholarships will be taken by trannies. hell, they may even have to allow trannies into the sororities. what a great time to be alive, i may actually live to see the fall of feminism. they have destroyed themselves from the inside and have no idea, what's at the end of the tunnel.

i have never cared about watching women sports cuz they are all boring, but i will gladly tune in and watch every match, if i can see them get knocked out by men legally in the octagon.

text:
my handmaid's costume arrived today. the hand bell came last week.  now i need to finish the sandwich board and posters i'll be displaying.  just in time for the first day of early voting. 
on voting days i'll be ringing out "shame, shame, shame" as voters head to the building to vote.  i want to remind voters of what's occurred under the current administration. items like: 
health care
separation of children from their parents
banning muslims from entering the us
the #metoo movement
trump's misogynistic actions
foisting christian religious views upon all of america
and on and on and on.

text:
i am a survivor. i am a survivor from a thing i thought i would never experience. a survivor of a thing i thought i would never move past. i am a survivor of sexual assault.
my goal on this page is to channel my anger and hurt into something that will have the ability to help those who are suffering or may have experienced trauma. i want to be apart of your recovery. this page will be used as a resource to inform people and help survivors. i want to include strategies for coping, information on various forms of assault, and give you a voice by giving you the opportunity to share your stories anonymously and be heard. #believeinyourvoice

.
.

text:
thanks to @nealthea for bringing this to my attention. @nytgender has been running a campaign called #thisis18, encouraging women to share advice theyâ€™d give their 18 year-old selves, along with a photo (feast your eyes upon this gem from my friendâ€™s dorm room - the original #selfie, circa 2004). so, here goes:

break up with your boyfriend before you leave for college. it will make freshman year much easier. donâ€™t be such a jerk to your mom - fast forward 14 years (ackkkkk) and youâ€™ll be spending more time on the phone with her than literally anyone else. youâ€™re beautiful. duke will try to make you think youâ€™re not, but you are. stop pretending to be unintelligent because you think your brainpower is a â€œturn offâ€ - donâ€™t wait until youâ€™re 25 to figure out that anyone turned off by your smarts isnâ€™t worth your time. enjoy every moment with your friends - even though luckily, the girls you ended high school with are still your close friends over a decade later. stop tanning. youâ€™re pasty - deal with it. your 30 year old skin will thank you. 
and the biggest one of all, the one thatâ€™s the most difficult to put down into words: report those men that assaulted you in your dorm room, and tell your story. you did not deserve what happened to you, and you deserve to feel safe and be heard. you are stronger than you think. you will get through this. and they deserve to be held accountable.

#metoo #thisis18 #flashback #retrospective #nytgender #nyt #thefutureisfemale

text:
iâ€™ve decided to pause my #90daydiary with @90_day_depression for a couple of weeks as halloween posts are cropping up more and more as we get closer to the holiday on all social media platforms. these are spurring on memories that have restarted my flashbacks, invasive thoughts, facial twitch and worst of all, sleep paralysis with hallucinations included in each episode. 
iâ€™ll possibly still be looking through and posting my usual but i donâ€™t want to pressure myself to think of something to write or process feelings out loud over the next fortnight at least, as they, i feel, are going to be feelings that i havenâ€™t had to go through yet and may need to fully process on my own or maybe even with a professional.
.

i will return to finish it as i am so invested in this and may take notes on my phone to post when i feel up to it, whether as part of the diary or not.

hereâ€™s a sickly sweet photo of @franklingthomas and myself falling to sleep together with him laid on a separate pillow above my head a couple of days ago to keep the cat posts up.

text:
::catharsis:: the chrysalis of your consciousness 
is in it's metamorphosis.

you're dying, 
liquifying. 
so, break... shatter. 
into a thousand tiny pieces.

let the stampedes of story rupture the silence

dissolve the compliance... to witness and consume violence. 
because the assault of the soul happens on all levels

and the system itself will conjure a cause for the rebel

the question is, where do you stand, and what do you stand to gain?

to live out the prophecy of your sovereignty.

you'll never be the same.

so alchemise the pain into medicine and then put yourself back together again.

rearranged

recoded

redefined... cos you could die all your metaphoric deaths and still wake up asleep, 
the bardo is for those who eternally seek.

you have to remember to find the reason to

rise. 
free.

wise.

you see how, now?

when all around purges tricky shadows, black and stark, 
there is always someone who will sit with you in the dark... until you remember that spark that resides,

deep, within your heart.

behind the face and the farce your old persona

the true you shines through

and gifts you a flicker, a shimmer... a glimmer of hope

when worlds collide at the end of a rope,

stand firm on the ground and turn it to a tether,

because this storm, no matter how big, is only weather.

so wash it all away and start a new dreaming

with curiosity you will see your life anchor with deeper meaning

there is as much beauty in the broken, as there is power in the process. 
the majick will be revealed when you start to focus.

artwork: 'autumn metamorphosis' by cynthia sheppard

text:
earlier this year, #donaldtrump was caught in a video that quickly went viral, showing the president refusing to share his umbrella with his wife and 12-year-old son. .
on monday, tv cameras captured trump in a similarly thoughtless moment on the white house lawn. as he and his wife, #melania trump, prepared to board the #marineone helicopter â€” starting their journey to the florida panhandle where,Â reuters reports, they arrived later monday â€” trump was distracted by reporters en route.
.
trump holds an umbrella over himself as he chats with reporters. but when #melaniatrump appears to join him, he makes no move to protect her from the rain with his #umbrella.
.
instead, trump walks several steps towards the tv cameras, leaving melania trump standing by herself in the rain. when he rejoins her, she moves herself under the umbrella, but he continues to make no move to share it with her.
.

text:
i wrote about hillary clinton's statements denying that bill clinton wasn't abusing his power when he started a sexual relationship with an 22-year-old intern. #linkinstories #linkinbio for full piece

i've been doing a lot of reading about trauma and it keeps coming back to the act of compassion. first, it's about building compassion about ourselves (yay #selfcompassion!), but through doing that i found it easier to practice compassion for others, too. it encourages me to think about context and what the other person may be feeling and facing.

what if we did that every time someone saysâ€”in good faithâ€”that they've been wronged? what if clinton used an answer based on what monica lewinsky feels about the situation. monica herself said clinton abused his power.  she's a grown woman now, too, no?

in a vanity fair essay, lewinsky wrote: " i now see how problematic it was that the two of us even got to a place where there was a question of consent. instead, the road that led there was littered with inappropriate abuse of authority, station, and privilege. (full stop.)" when it comes to power and consent, what's *legal* isn't what's always *ethical* or *right*â€”and i believe the onus was on the president to do the right thing and set that boundary. his privilege and power allowed him to feel comfortable to do itâ€”and then lewinsky ends up being publicly bullied as she's used as a political pawn.

the best way to understand harm is to talk to the people who've been harmed. even if it is not intentional there's still value in taking time to sit and consider their point of view, even if it's to make you more sure of your own. i think if we used this approach in every aspect of life, believing survivors will come much more naturally.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#consent #abuse #metoo #monicalewinsky #antibullying #compassion #affirmativeconsent

text:
i am disappointed at all the bullshit that i hear of young models being sexually harassed or manipulated in the sacramento community and it is not okay. for those who are being accused please realize you are shooting models for art or for your job not as a sex hook up. to play it safe take every shoot as if it is your paying job to be professional and respectful. it is disappointing to hear some stories from young models dealing with sexual harassment from photographers who are well known in the community. even though some may doubt the victims' credibility, please be aware it also takes great strength and courage for these girls to speak up against their accusers to the public.

i have gone through this multiple times as well at different work places when i even had credible evidence against my harassers. unfortunately in a man's world the companies did not take sufficient action to address my issue which resulted me to either quit my job or continue to work in a hostile work environment for a little longer before i found another job.

thus be the change. for photographers out there please be sensitive and respectful to all the models you shoot with. no women wants to be forced to do something they are not comfortable to do or what you ask them to do. plus keep your hands to yourself. it is not okay to touch a model or flirt with them as it is not professional.

i want to shout out to @vintage_barbiedoll and @rhibogart for being courageous and strong to speak out about this issue and to other beautiful models who directly experienced the harassment from these photographers. plus shout out to the other photographers like @laceymc for speaking out about this issue as well. all of you are inspiring and courageous women. #bethechange #respect #inspire

me too.
if all the women who have been sexually harassed or assaulted wrote "me too." as a post, we might give people a sense of the magnitude of the problem.  keep the awareness going.  awareness is the basis for change.
â €â €â €â €â €â €

one year ago today.
this.
#metoo
i knew i wanted to say something â€œpubliclyâ€ about what had happened a year prior, on saturday, october 15, 2016.
â €â €â €â €â €â €
to honor my experience.
to honor being alive, bruises and scrapes healed.
to honor the courage and strength it took to do all the emotional and psychological and somatic healing work i had done up to that point â€” all the little moment-by-moment steps, all the big moves, all those actions in between.
â €â €â €â €â €â €
i remember being anxious all day, not knowing how to say or what to say about it all.
yet it felt important to say something, anything ...
â €â €â €â €â €â €
...and just as the clock was nearing midnight, on the 1 year anniversary of being raped by a former friend and work colleague, a â€œnormal guy,â€ i opened ig and there it was
â €â €â €â €â €â €
#metoo
#metoo
#metoo
â €â €â €â €â €â €
i am so grateful for the #metoomovement to give voice to me and so many others.
â €â €â €â €â €â €
itâ€™s not over. itâ€™s never fully over.
our relationship to our experience just changes.
and we can turn our pain into medicine, into advocacy, into action.
â €â €â €â €â €â €
i am grateful to be able to do just that.
â €â €â €â €â €â €
in love and solidarity with all survivors â€”

i see you.
i hear you.
i believe you.
keep going.
you are loved.
